{
  "doc_id": "58335",
  "text": "These discoveries were presaged by the curious phenomenon of transgene silencing, which is mainly found in plants [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and linked to both antisense RNA and small RNA-directed DNA methylation, thus indicating transcriptional and post-transcriptional silencing [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Mechanistic analyses of these silencing mechanisms showed that exogenous double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) is processed into short fragments (known as small interfering RNAs (siRNAs)) with similar sizes to mi RNAs, which implies that mi RNAs may represent a similar endogenous system. This hypothesis was confirmed and led to the elucidation of natural dsRNA precursors in stem-loop structures [CITATION_5] , as well as the identification of key genes and enzymes involved in their biogenesis and function, notably Drosha [CITATION_6] , Dicer [CITATION_7] and several Argonaute (AGO) proteins [CITATION_8] . AGO proteins were already known to have central roles in differentiation and development [CITATION_9] but are now known to also be involved in defence against RNA viruses in many organisms [CITATION_10] . Drosha and exportin 5 are involved in the cleavage and export of dsRNA precursors from the nucleus to the cytoplasm [CITATION_11] , where they are further processed by Dicer to small (21-24-nucleotide) dsRNA moieties. One strand of the dsRNA is loaded into the AGO component of the RNAinduced silencing complex (RISC), which also comprises other proteins [CITATION_12] . The RISC is guided by the small RNA strand to complementary RNA targets, which are subsequently silenced by translational repression and/or RNA destabilization [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] (FIG. 3) .",
